      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling After a Co-Owner Dies: Surviving Joint Tenant, Transmission Application, and the Queensland Sale Process
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        How to lodge a transmission application, what documents the buyer's solicitor will want to see, and how the surviving spouse can navigate a Queensland sale calmly without inheriting a deceased estate process they do not need.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The most common Queensland ownership structure for couples is joint tenancy. Two people, two names on the title, equal legal interest, and the right of survivorship: when one owner dies, the deceased's interest passes automatically to the survivor without going through the will. The survivor becomes the sole owner of the property by operation of law, with no probate required for the real estate.</p>

      <p>When the surviving spouse later decides to sell, the process is more straightforward than many people expect. It is not a deceased estate sale, it is not blocked while probate proceeds, and it does not require the executor of the deceased's will to be involved in the property at all. What is required is a transmission application to bring the title into the surviving owner's sole name, and a careful, calm Queensland sale process that gives the survivor space to make decisions in their own time.</p>

      <p>This article walks through the legal mechanism, the practical documents needed, the timing considerations, the contract and disclosure questions, the capital gains and tax implications, and the emotional and pacing considerations for sellers in this situation. The tone is intentionally practical. People going through this process have already lost a partner; the last thing they need is administrative confusion layered on top.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Joint tenancy and survivorship: the legal mechanism</h2>
      <p>Under Queensland property law, joint tenants hold an undivided interest in the whole of the property, with no defined share. When one joint tenant dies, the right of survivorship operates: the deceased's interest is treated as having ended, and the surviving joint tenant continues to hold the whole interest. The deceased's will has no effect on the property, because the property does not form part of the deceased's estate for distribution purposes.</p>

      <p>This is different to tenants in common, where each owner has a defined share (often 50/50, but not always) that passes through their will. If the structure on title is tenants in common, the deceased's share forms part of the estate and the executor handles the sale of that share, which is a different process. The first step for any surviving co-owner is to confirm which structure is on the title. A title search will show this. Many sellers assume their title says "joint tenants" because that is what they intended; the actual title sometimes says "tenants in common in equal shares", and the legal path differs.</p>

      <p>Where the title is held jointly, the surviving owner is the sole legal owner from the moment of death. The transmission application is a process to update the title register to reflect the legal reality. It is administrative, not transactional. The surviving owner can sign agency agreements, consider listing decisions, and even sign sale contracts before the transmission is registered, although the transmission must be registered before settlement so the title can transfer cleanly.</p>

      <p>For a deeper comparison of the two ownership structures, see our notes on <a href="/insights/joint-tenants-tenants-in-common-selling-queensland" style="color:#f5d07a;">joint tenants vs tenants in common when selling in Queensland</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The transmission application, step by step</h2>
      <p>The transmission application is lodged with Titles Queensland by the surviving owner, usually with help from a solicitor. The required elements are straightforward.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Form 5A Transmission Application by Survivor.</strong> The standard Titles Queensland form. It identifies the surviving owner, the deceased owner, the title reference, and the lot on plan.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Certified copy of the death certificate.</strong> A formal death certificate issued by the Queensland Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages (or the equivalent interstate registry if the death occurred outside Queensland). Funeral home documents are not sufficient.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Identity verification.</strong> The surviving owner's identity must be verified to standard Titles Queensland requirements, usually by a solicitor or a registered identity verifier.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Lodgement fee.</strong> A modest registration fee payable to Titles Queensland.</p>

      <p>Lodgement can usually be electronic via PEXA where a solicitor is instructed. Once lodged, registration typically happens within one to three weeks for a clean application. Once registered, the title shows the survivor as sole owner and the deceased owner is removed.</p>

      <p>For the broader context of how Queensland titles work and what a title search actually contains, see our notes on <a href="/insights/how-to-read-queensland-certificate-of-title-seller" style="color:#f5d07a;">how to read a Queensland certificate of title</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Timing the sale relative to the transmission</h2>
      <p>Sellers often ask whether they need to wait for the transmission to register before listing. They do not. The right of survivorship is automatic, the surviving owner is the sole legal owner from the moment of death, and listing, marketing, and even contract execution can proceed in parallel with the transmission process. The only hard constraint is that the transmission must be registered before settlement, so the title can transfer to the buyer in the survivor's name alone.</p>

      <p>In practice, most surviving owners lodge the transmission early in the listing process, ideally before the agency authority is signed, so that by the time a contract is reached the title already shows the survivor as sole owner. This makes the contract paperwork simpler, the buyer's due diligence smoother, and the settlement process predictable. It also avoids the awkwardness of presenting the buyer with a title that still shows the deceased's name.</p>

      <p>Buyers and their solicitors are usually comfortable with a transmission in flight, provided the contract addresses the timing and the seller's solicitor confirms the transmission will be completed before settlement. Where the transmission is straightforward (death certificate clean, identity uncomplicated), this is rarely an issue. Where there is any complication (dispute over the deceased's identity, missing death certificate, interstate registration), the listing should wait until the transmission is registered.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers' solicitors actually check</h2>
      <p>A buyer's solicitor will run a title search at the start of due diligence and again before settlement. They will look for the survivor's sole ownership, any encumbrances (mortgages, easements, caveats), and whether any interests have been lodged that complicate the transfer.</p>

      <p>If the title still shows both names at contract date, the buyer's solicitor will want a written undertaking from the seller's solicitor that the transmission is in progress, the death certificate is in hand, and the transmission will be registered before settlement. Provided that undertaking is given, the contract proceeds normally. If the title shows the survivor as sole owner already, no further reassurance is needed.</p>

      <p>Some buyers' solicitors ask whether there is any prospect of a family provision claim against the deceased's estate that could affect the property. The legal answer is no: the property does not form part of the deceased's estate for family provision purposes if it was held in joint tenancy. A claimant may make claims against the estate, but the joint tenancy property is not a target of those claims in the ordinary course. A confirmation of this from the seller's solicitor is usually enough.</p>

      <p>For the related but distinct case of a sole owner who has died (and the executor must sell), see our notes on <a href="/insights/selling-deceased-estate-queensland-executor" style="color:#f5d07a;">selling a deceased estate as executor</a>. The mechanism, the documents, and the timeline are different from a surviving joint tenant sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Capital gains and tax considerations</h2>
      <p>The capital gains position for a surviving joint tenant is more favourable than many sellers assume, particularly where the property was a main residence.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Main residence throughout.</strong> If the property was the main residence of the couple throughout the period of ownership and the survivor continues to live there or sells within the standard allowable period after the death, the main residence exemption usually fully exempts any capital gain on sale. Specialist advice is needed to confirm this for the specific facts.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Cost base reset for the deceased's half.</strong> For tax purposes, the deceased's half interest is treated as having been acquired by the survivor at its market value as at the date of death. The survivor's own original half retains its original cost base. So even where the property has been an investment, the survivor often has a stepped-up cost base on half the property, which materially reduces capital gain on later sale.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Mixed-use history.</strong> Where the property was a main residence for part of the period and an investment for another part, or where it was rented out for a period after the death, the calculation becomes more complex. A specialist Queensland accountant should run the actual numbers rather than relying on rules of thumb.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Stamp duty.</strong> No transfer duty applies on the transmission itself, because the transfer is by operation of law rather than by transaction. The survivor does not pay stamp duty to bring the title into their sole name.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Mortgages and other lender questions</h2>
      <p>Where a mortgage was held in joint names with a lender, the survivor becomes solely liable on the surviving facility. Most Australian lenders handle this routinely once the death certificate is provided, with the loan continuing in the survivor's name on the same terms. Lenders sometimes use the moment to review serviceability, particularly where the deceased's income was a meaningful contributor; where serviceability is now a concern, the conversation about refinance or sale becomes more pressing.</p>

      <p>Where a mortgage exists at the time of sale, the standard sale settlement process applies: the loan is paid out from sale proceeds at settlement, the mortgage is discharged, and the net proceeds flow to the survivor as sole owner. There is nothing structurally unusual about a sale of a joint-tenancy-survivor property compared to any other Brisbane sale, once the transmission is sorted.</p>

      <p>If the survivor is contemplating staying in the property and refinancing rather than selling, that is a separate decision, and the financial and emotional analysis should be deliberate rather than reactive. Selling the family home in the immediate aftermath of a partner's death is sometimes the right call and sometimes not. The pressure to "sort everything out quickly" often produces decisions that are later regretted; pacing matters here more than in most sales.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pacing the sale: practical and emotional</h2>
      <p>There is no Queensland legal deadline that requires a surviving spouse to sell within a particular timeframe. The capital gains main residence rules give a generous window where the property can continue to be treated as a main residence after death, and the practical pressures (financial, family, occupancy) usually shape the timing more than legal requirements do.</p>

      <p>For many surviving spouses, the right pacing is to wait long enough that the decision to sell is being made calmly rather than reactively, but not so long that the property and the survivor's circumstances drift in a direction that produces a worse outcome. Six to twelve months after the death is a common window for the decision to crystallise, sometimes longer. Selling within the first three months is occasionally the right call, but should be a positive, considered decision rather than a default response to financial or emotional pressure.</p>

      <p>The agent and solicitor handling the sale need to be people the survivor trusts, who can carry the operational load, and who can communicate clearly without rushing. The sale of a long-held family home after a partner's death is one of the most emotionally significant transactions a person ever undertakes; it deserves a campaign run with care, with patience, and with attention to the survivor's pace rather than the agent's preferences.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where this differs from a deceased estate sale</h2>
      <p>The key practical differences are worth restating. A surviving joint tenant sale has no executor, no probate (for the property), no estate distribution to manage, and no will-related disputes that affect the property. The surviving owner is the sole decision maker. Contracts are signed by the survivor alone. Settlement proceeds flow to the survivor. The administrative load is materially lighter than a deceased estate sale where a sole owner has died.</p>

      <p>A surviving joint tenant sale also has no requirement for executor sign-off on agency agreements, no need for the property to be marketed within a particular timeframe to satisfy beneficiary expectations, and no risk of family provision claims affecting the property. The legal cleanliness of the position is one of the unsung benefits of the joint tenancy structure for couples.</p>

      <p>Where the deceased was the sole owner, or where the deceased and survivor held the property as tenants in common, the path is different and the executor process applies. For that case, see <a href="/insights/selling-deceased-estate-brisbane" style="color:#f5d07a;">selling a deceased estate in Brisbane</a> and <a href="/insights/deceased-estate-probate-timeline-brisbane" style="color:#f5d07a;">the deceased estate probate timeline</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical pre-listing checklist for a surviving joint tenant</h2>
      <p>1. Order a current title search to confirm the ownership structure is joint tenancy. 2. Obtain a certified copy of the death certificate from the relevant registry. 3. Engage a Queensland solicitor to lodge the transmission application. 4. Notify the lender (if any) of the death and confirm the mortgage continuation arrangement. 5. Engage a specialist accountant to confirm the capital gains position before the sale is committed to. 6. Take time to make the decision to sell calmly rather than reactively. 7. Choose an agent and solicitor who can carry the operational load with care. 8. Prepare a buyer information pack that anticipates the questions about ownership and timing. 9. Set the listing date with consideration for the transmission timing and the survivor's emotional pacing. 10. Run a campaign that protects the survivor's privacy and decision-making space.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bottom line</h2>
      <p>A Queensland sale by a surviving joint tenant is mechanically straightforward. The right of survivorship makes the survivor the sole owner; the transmission application updates the register; the sale proceeds as a normal Brisbane transaction with the survivor as the sole vendor. The complexity is rarely legal and almost always emotional and practical: choosing the right pacing, the right team, and the right time. Sellers who give themselves space to make the decision well usually achieve a calm, clean sale. Sellers who rush, or who try to handle the administrative work alone in the immediate aftermath, often regret elements of the process. The Queensland law works for the survivor here; the most useful thing the survivor can do is let it.</p>

